<table width="640" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
  <tr>
    <td width="117"><img src="../../../images/checklist.gif" width="103" height="124"></td>
    <td width="516"><div align="center">
      <p>Tools and Forms Used for Documenting </p>
      <p align="left">At Shari's you have many company forms, reports and systems to be used for the documenting process. </p>
    </div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><p><strong>Training and Selection Documentation</strong>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Orientation Checklist: filled out during orientation and located in the employee file - documents the employee and manager review all topics on the list.</li>
        <li>Safety Orientation Checklist: Filled out during the safety orientation - documents that employee reviewed Shari's safety program, MSDS training, safe lifting training and went on a safety tour. Document is located in the employee file.</li>
        <li>File Indexes: Filled out during orientation, training and ongoing throughout the employee's employment. One file index is located in the employee's file and records and contains orientation documents, videos viewed, performance reviews and references notations in the manager's log. The other file index is located in the employee's training file and records the training received and all tests that have been taken.</li>
        <li>Interviewing Binder: The interviewing binder should document questions asked to employees during the interview process as well as when interview were conducted. </li>
        <li>POS and RAS Reports: POS and RAS reports contain employee schedules and document employee attendance: days worked, clocking in for shifts and meetings as well as proper break procedures. </li>
      </ul>
    <p><strong>Performance Issue Documentation:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Manager's Log: The manager's log is used to document such things as guest complaints and compliments involving employees, tardiness, employee requests that need follow up.</li>
      <li>Suspension Notice: Used to document a suspension pending review or result of a drug test.</li>
      <li>Disciplinary Notice: General form to notify employees of poor performance or violation of company policies. The form follows the standard written documentation format and is recommended for most employee performance issues.</li>
      <li>Incident Statement: This form is used to gather information about an incident that occurred: accident, witness statements for investigations, documentation of other employee conversations that are not disciplinary in nature, and employee compliments. </li>
      <li>Request Off and Shift Change Forms: These forms are used to document and record manager's responses to time off and shift change requests.</li>
      <li>Leave of Absence Form: Requests for medical, pregnancy, parental and personal leaves are documented and submitted for approval on this form. </li>
    </ul>    
    <p><strong>Food Cost and Accounting Issues:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Manager's Log: The manager's log can be used to document borrows and and returns between stores. It can also be used to document substitutions made by vendors and employee training issues involving food.</li>
      <li>Prep List, PPQC, Food Cost Audits, Inventory: These forms are used to document the quality, amounts and usage of food. These forms help us identify, analyze and correct food loss issues.</li>
      <li>POS and RAS Reports: Our compute system generates various reports that help a manager identify and control food cost and food quality. Computer reports also assist a manager in locating the invalid discounting as well as cash shortages.</li>
      </ul>    
    <p><strong>Building Equipment and Store Issues:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Manager's Log: The managers log is used to document repairs needed and completed at the store. Manager's logs are also used to document customer complaints, accidents and general information about the happenings on a particular shift.</li>
      <li>Inspection Reports: Inspections may be conducted by people outside the company. The health department, OSHA, fire department and our dish chemical company all inspect our facilities at various times. Anytime you receive such an inspection, you should request a copy of the paper work and keep it in your store files.</li>
      <li>POS and RAS Reports: Store performance in the areas of labor control and sales and profit are documented by POS and RAS reports. <br>
      </li>
    </ul>    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr valign="top">
    <td colspan="2"><div align="center">
      <p><img src="../../../images/icons/test4.gif" width="54" height="71"> <strong>Format For Written Documentation <img src="../../../images/icons/test4.gif" width="54" height="71"></strong></p>
      <p align="left">It is important that you know that any form of documentation that we have can be subpoenaed by a court. It is therefore important that your documentation, regardless of the form you are using, be professional. You need to write neatly and spell correctly. In addition, make sure that your language is respectful, do not make flippant or derogatory remarks that you wouldn't want read in a court of law. Please use the following format when writing.<br>
        <br>
        1. Begin with a title statement about the purpose of the warning, for example: use of offensive language.</p>
      <p align="left">2. Next, write a statement of the problem or violation, for example: as of today, your offensive language has not ceased.</p>
      <p align="left">3. Prepare a statement explaining how the employee's action or performance had a negative impact on the store's operations, for example: The employees and guests at the restaurant are offended by your language. </p>
      <p align="left">4. Write a statement of Shari's policy, or customary standards regarding the situation, for example: This type of language is a direct violation of Shari's Codes of Conduct under General Offenses as listed in your employee handbook.</p>
      <p align="left">5. Next, list previous verbal or written warnings about the same or related problem, for example: On June 1, 2004, you were verbally warned....You have been counseled on this issue, told that it is not appropriate, and asked to stop many times: May 17, 2004; May 28, 2004; and today, June 9, 2004.</p>
      <p align="left">6. Write a summary of the agreement reached with the employee on corrective action to be taken, and the period of time fro corrective action to occur, or if no agreement was reached, a statement to that effect, for example: You agreed that you would be more careful and not use offensive language while at work.</p>
      <p align="left">7. Finally, write a statement of the next action management will take, for example: Should it continue, further disciplinary action will be taken, up to and including termination.</p>
      <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>
    </div></td>
  </tr>
